  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>How to fix a bad AeroPress cup without starting over</h2>
      <p>
        If your coffee tastes <strong>sour</strong> — sharp like lemon water instead of sweet like citrus — your method is usually
        under-extracting. That just means the water did not pull enough flavor from the grounds. Before you tear up the whole recipe,
        change one thing. Grind a little finer, steep a little longer, or use slightly hotter water. The classic standard method is
        the easiest place to learn this because the cup stays clean enough that the problem is obvious.
      </p>
      <p>
        If your cup tastes <strong>bitter</strong> or hollow, back off. Dark roasts especially can go from chocolatey to harsh fast.
        Lower the water temperature, press more gently, or shorten the steep. This is why I like the low-bitterness dark roast method
        so much. It gives darker beans a little breathing room instead of beating them up with heat and over-contact time.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the coffee tastes <strong>muddy</strong>, the issue is often body without clarity. A metal filter or concentrate-style
        recipe can do that if your grind is too fine or your coffee is producing too many fines — basically tiny dust-like particles.
        That is when a better grinder helps. The <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">best AeroPress grind size guide</a>
        matters more than another random recipe from social media, because grind changes show up in the cup immediately.
      </p>
      <p>
        If your press feels <strong>way too hard</strong>, do not force it. That usually means the grind is too fine or the filter is
        clogging. Forcing the press is how people end up wearing coffee. Back off, go a touch coarser, and keep the plunge smooth.
        Think steady hand pressure, not a gym rep. AeroPress works best when it feels controlled.
      </p>
      <p>
        The biggest mistake is changing three things at once. Keep the dose the same, keep the water amount the same, and then adjust
        one variable. That is boring advice. It is also the fastest way to get delicious coffee on purpose instead of by accident.
        If you want a tighter workflow, pair this page with our guides to <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-time.html">brew time</a>
        and <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-temp.html">brew temperature</a> so your tweaks stay simple.
      </p>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">How to choose your method</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Pick by cup style first.</strong> If you like cleaner, brighter coffee, start with the classic paper-filter method.
        If you want more body and a denser mouthfeel, move toward no-drip immersion or concentrate recipes. That one decision gets
        you closer faster than obsessing over tiny timer differences.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Then look at how much morning effort you can actually tolerate.</strong> The standard method wins because it asks for
        very little and still tastes great. The Prismo setup is still easy, but it adds one more part. A precise kettle and scale
        are useful upgrades, though they only matter if you are the kind of person who will use them every day.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Roast level changes the best answer.</strong> Medium roasts are forgiving and play nicely with almost every method.
        Darker roasts usually taste better when you cool the water a little and avoid over-extracting them. Lighter roasts often
        like a bit more heat and a little more contact time so the cup does not come out thin and sour.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Travel is its own category.</strong> At home, you can chase tiny improvements. On the road, the best recipe is the one
        you can repeat half-awake in a hotel room without covering the desk in grounds. That is why the AeroPress Go earns its spot.
        It keeps the whole thing compact and cuts down the chance that you skip coffee altogether.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Do not ignore cleanup tolerance.</strong> AeroPress is already pretty low-mess, but some methods still feel smoother
        than others. Paper-filter standard brewing is basically rinse, pop, done. Metal-filter and add-on recipes can be worth it,
        but only if the fuller cup matters enough that you will not resent the extra rinse every morning.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>My practical ranking is simple.</strong> Start with standard if you are new. Move to no-drip immersion if you want
        more body. Use concentrate recipes when you specifically want a stronger base. Keep the travel method for portable brewing,
        and use lower-temp dark-roast tweaks when bitterness is your main problem. That order saves money because you only buy extra
        gear when you know exactly what problem it solves.
      </p>

